<p>In <a href="/wiki/Greek_mythology" title="Greek mythology">Greek mythology</a>, <b>Medusa</b> (<a href="/wiki/Greek_language" title="Greek language">Greek</a>: <span lang="el" xml:lang="el">Μέδουσα (Médousa</span>), "guardian, protectress"<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>) was a <a href="/wiki/Gorgon" title="Gorgon">gorgon</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Chthonic" title="Chthonic">chthonic</a> female monster; gazing upon her would turn onlookers to stone. She was beheaded by the hero <a href="/wiki/Perseus" title="Perseus">Perseus</a>, who thereafter used her head as a weapon<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> until giving it to the goddess <a href="/wiki/Athena" title="Athena">Athena</a> to place on her <a href="/wiki/Aegis" title="Aegis">shield</a>. In <a href="/wiki/Classical_antiquity" title="Classical antiquity">classical antiquity</a> and today, the image of the head of Medusa finds expression in the <a href="/wiki/Apotropaic_magic" title="Apotropaic magic">evil-averting device</a> known as the <i><a href="/wiki/Gorgoneion" title="Gorgoneion" class="mw-redirect">Gorgoneion</a></i>. She also has two gorgon sisters.</p>
