<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> (Pythian Ode 12). Noted by <a href="/w/index.php?title=Marjorie_J._Milne&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Marjorie J. Milne (page does not exist)">Marjorie J. Milne</a> in discussing a <a href="/wiki/Red-figure_pottery" title="Red-figure pottery">red-figured vase</a> in the style of <a href="/wiki/Polygnotos_(vase_painter)" title="Polygnotos (vase painter)">Polygnotos</a>, ca. 450-30 BC, in the <a href="/wiki/Metropolitan_Museum_of_Art" title="Metropolitan Museum of Art">Metropolitan Museum of Art</a>; Milne noted that "It is one of the earliest illustrations of the story to show the Gorgon not as a hideous monster but as a beautiful woman. Art in this respect lagged behind poetry." (Marjorie J. Milne, "Perseus and Medusa on an Attic Vase" <i>The Metropolitan Museum of Art Bulletin</i> New Series, <b>4</b>.5 (January 1946, pp. 126-130) 126.p.)</li>
